      <?php include "0.php";?> and later that year the child was born, in a busy urban hospital on the humid autumn evening of November 8, 1985. If he&rsquo;d been a girl, his parents would have named him Megan, but instead his parents named him William.</p>
      <p>At the age of fifty-three he lay on a cot in the cabin of a train, wearing crimson pajamas and some rubber sandals, writing a verse of poetry in a notebook. A doha for a new collection. Beyond the window, dark clouds were floating through the sky above the mountain. Ice was shimmering on the cedar trees. Snow gleamed. He could smell the chai in the mug on the table. He could feel the cot trembling as the train clattered along the tracks. Glancing back down at the notebook, he pressed the tip of the pen to the paper, about to write another word, and then he suddenly became aware of a shuddering movement, and he noticed that snow was tumbling from the summit of the mountain, cascading in powdery crashes down the slope, smashing through boulders, and a moment later the avalanche struck the train, flipping the train from the tracks. His body was eventually discovered, but the poem was never found.</p>
